  "prompt": "Why do Indians think a lot about what others think?",
  "response": "This is a complex sociological and cultural phenomenon. Several factors contribute to this tendency in Indian society:\n\n1. Collectivist Culture\n- Strong emphasis on family and community\n- Social harmony is highly valued\n- Individual reputation affects entire family/community\n\n2. Social Hierarchy\n- Traditional societal structures are hierarchical\n- People's opinions and judgments matter significantly\n- Social status and respect are crucial\n\n3. Historical and Cultural Context\n- Long history of close-knit communities\n- Social acceptance has been traditionally important for survival\n- Interdependence is more prevalent than individualism\n\n4. Educational and Social Conditioning\n- Children are often taught to prioritize others' perceptions\n- Social approval is seen as a measure of personal worth\n- Conformity is often encouraged over individual expression\n\n5. Psychological Factors\n- Fear of social criticism\n- High value placed on reputation\n- Concern about potential social consequences\n\n6. Economic and Social Pressures\n- Limited opportunities make social networks important\n- Competition in education and professional spaces\n- Social connections can provide economic advantages\n\nThese factors combine to create a social environment where others' opinions are considered significantly important. However, it's important to note that this is a generalization, and individual experiences can vary widely.",
